===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/flæg/}}
*{{audio|en-us-flag.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*:Rhymes: [[rhymes:English:-æɡ|-æɡ]]

===Etymology 1===
Of uncertain origin; compare Dutch [[flag#Dutch|flag]], Danish [[flæg]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}
# any of various plants with sword-shaped leaves, especially [[iris]]es; specifically, ''Iris pseudacorus''

====Derived terms====
*[[sweet flag]]

===Etymology 2===
Probably of Scandinavian origin; compare Icelandic [[flag#Icelandic|flag]].

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# ''(obsolete except in dialects)'' a slice of [[turf]], a [[sod]]
# a slab of stone, a [[flagstone]].

====Verb====
{{en-verb|flag|g|ed}}

# To lay down flagstones.
#: ''Fred is planning to flag his patio this weekend.''

===Etymology 3===
[[Image:Flyingrainbowflag.JPG|right|thumb|a flag]]
Origin unknown.

[[Image:Example.jpg]]

====Adjective====
{{en-adj-notcomp}}

# Of or pertaining to an [[admiral]], [[commodore]], or [[general]] officer.
#:''Captains park in the second row, '''flag''' officers next to the building.''

====Verb====
{{en-verb|flag|g|ing}}

# To mark with a flag, especially to indicate the importance of
# (often with ''down'') To signal to, especially to stop a passing vehicle etc.
#: ''Please flag a taxi down for me.''
# ''(intransitive)'' To [[weaken]], become feeble.
#: ''His strength flagged toward the end of the race.
# {{cattag|Computing}}: To signal (an event).
#: ''The compiler flagged three errors.''
# {{cattag|Computing}}: To set a program variable to ''true''.
#: ''Flag the debug option before running the program.''

